elements.2211.03160_abd563524cab1aa590a98961322d0: In this work, we have adopted a hybrid OpenACC and MPI approach for accelerated thermal LB simulation on multi-GPUs
elements.2211.03160_f0d882f04629a9488a96da2228541: We adopt the double distribution function-based thermal LB model, namely, D2Q9 + D2Q5 in the 2D simulation, and D3Q19 + D3Q7 in the 3D simulation
elements.2211.03160_b3a2f565b50106e6c7ee6dd6912ca: With a single NVIDIA A100 GPU, the 2D simulation achieved 1.93 GLUPS with a grid number of
elements.2211.03160_bcb216c9aef10f8fea69783206b05: and the 3D thermal LB simulation achieves 1.04 GLUPS with a grid number of
elements.2211.03160_47298c6bb351cb1991540edd846a7: In a naive implementation to extend to multi-GPUs, we used mono-direction partitioning of the computation domain, however, the code was not scalable to more than 8 GPUs in the 3D simulation
elements.2211.03160_8494ac8bf3194cee4e9226347c2a2: To further boost the parallel performance, we adopted three optimization strategies: block partitioning, overlapping communications with computations, and concurrent computation
elements.2211.03160_40e4b1611949b68a2ed35b7e1fa9a: With block partitioning, the domain is decomposed in more than one dimension, and it decreases the amount of data that needs to be transferred
elements.2211.03160_27a8d7e970b7b2e913309bdac278a: By overlapping the communications with computations, communication overhead is hidden behind the kernel runtime
elements.2211.03160_3701e040bbd7692264e4dee418a5e: Using concurrent computation, task parallelism can be exploited to better utilize the GPU hardware resources
elements.2211.03160_b669a3ca7e1acbc74d0b5a5b4ea31: After adopting these optimization strategies, we demonstrate that the parallel performance can be significantly improved
elements.2211.03160_23adabc11a6e465a2607ae0c6bed0: In the strong scaling test, using 16 GPUs, the 2D simulation achieved 30.42 GLUPS and the 3D simulation achieved 14.52 GLUPS
elements.2211.03160_20fba70d0126705f6c29b80ea0565: It should be noted that all performance measurements are based on double-precision floating-point arithmetic, which ensures simulation accuracy
elements.2211.03160_0efbef1152bf230ab6f00d6065cea: *Appendix: Comparison of the parallel performance on CPUs versus GPUs
elements.2211.03160_7437d4c5fbb7dd1737442de3f82c4: In the appendix, we summarize the MLUPS of the GPU code adopting the optimization strategies discussed in Section
elements.2211.03160_d7fe8c9b178cf929b888fe0f61011: As a comparison, we provide the MLUPS of a CPU code, which is developed with a hybrid MPI and OpenMP approach
elements.2211.03160_fcf4d4e48f8f6b5ad5361a33e1985: The CPU code is based on a hierarchical two-level parallelization, where the first-level parallelization applies MPI domain decomposition to the simulation domain, and the second-level parallelization uses OpenMP parallel regions for loops within a subdomain
elements.2211.03160_d216bd11cd762522824259a7e4968: Such a hybrid MPI + OpenMP approach can reduce the memory usage and overhead associated with MPI calls
elements.2211.03160_5025fc59c9f1edcf5afab1df659f1: For experiments on the CPU cluster, each node is equipped with two Intel Xeon 6258R CPUs (i.e., 56 cores within a node), we assign 4 MPI processes on each node with 14 OpenMP threads per MPI process
elements.2211.03160_44e85bff80473b137aa5809fa2079: This choice is a compromise between two factors: first, more OpenMP threads reduces the corresponding number of MPI processes, which leads to better communication performances; secondly, more OpenMP threads increases the overhead associated with OpenMP constructs and remote memory accesses across sockets
elements.2211.03160_449ad31a08bd247c3e021a3983cf7: For all the cases investigated, our test results showed that on each node, the combination of 4 MPI processes
elements.2211.03160_b8afbc7d8715ec13b2161a401d619: 14 OpenMP threads works slightly better than that of 7 MPI processes
elements.2211.03160_179a736cc0e856c9e0b62aa94d46f: that in the strong scaling test, both our CPU code and GPU code scale well.
